Charles Bukowski was a prolific writer known for his raw and gritty exploration of the human experience, often delving into themes of love, loneliness, alcoholism, and the struggles of the everyman. Here’s a collection of quotes from his poetry, novels, and other writings:

---

### **On Writing and Creativity**
1. "Writing about a writer’s block is better than not writing at all." (*Pulp*)
2. "Find what you love and let it kill you." (*The People Look Like Flowers at Last*)
3. "Sometimes you climb out of bed in the morning and you think, I’m not going to make it, but you laugh inside—remembering all the times you’ve felt that way." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)
4. "If you're going to try, go all the way. Otherwise, don’t even start." (*Factotum*)
5. "Poetry is what happens when nothing else can." (*What Matters Most is How Well You Walk Through the Fire*)
6. "An intellectual says a simple thing in a hard way. An artist says a hard thing in a simple way." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)
7. "You begin saving the world by saving one man at a time; all else is grandiose romanticism or politics." (*Ham on Rye*)
8. "People run from rain but sit in bathtubs full of water." (*Love is a Dog from Hell*)
9. "What matters most is how well you walk through the fire." (*What Matters Most is How Well You Walk Through the Fire*)
10. "We are here to drink beer. We are here to kill war. We are here to laugh at the odds and live our lives so well that Death will tremble to take us." (*The Night Torn Mad With Footsteps*)

### **On Life and Existence**
11. "Some people never go crazy. What truly horrible lives they must lead." (*Post Office*)
12. "We are like roses that have never bothered to bloom when we should have bloomed and it is as if the sun has become disgusted with waiting." (*The People Look Like Flowers at Last*)
13. "I wanted the whole world or nothing." (*Post Office*)
14. "The problem with the world is that the intelligent people are full of doubts, while the stupid ones are full of confidence." (*Tales of Ordinary Madness*)
15. "You have to die a few times before you can really live." (*The People Look Like Flowers at Last*)
16. "You have to know how to accept rejection and reject acceptance." (*Factotum*)
17. "How in the hell could a man enjoy being awakened at 6:30 AM by an alarm clock, leap out of bed, dress, force-feed, shit, piss, brush teeth, and fight traffic to get to a place where essentially you made lots of money for somebody else and were asked to be grateful for the opportunity to do so?" (*Factotum*)
18. "I didn’t have any friends at all, because I didn’t want any friends." (*Ham on Rye*)
19. "The free soul is rare, but you know it when you see it—basically because you feel good, very good, when you are near or with them." (*Tales of Ordinary Madness*)
20. "I have never been lonely. I’ve been in a room—I’ve felt suicidal. I’ve been depressed. I’ve felt awful—awful beyond all, but I never felt that one other person could enter that room and cure what was bothering me." (*Factotum*)

### **On Love and Relationships**
21. "Love is a fog that burns with the first daylight of reality." (*Women*)
22. "We don’t even ask for happiness, just a little less pain." (*The Last Night of the Earth Poems*)
23. "You have to die a few times before you can really live." (*The People Look Like Flowers at Last*)
24. "Love is kind of like when you see a fog in the morning when you wake up before the sun comes out. It’s just there a little while and then it burns away." (*Women*)
25. "There is a loneliness in this world so great that you can see it in the slow movement of the hands of a clock." (*Love is a Dog from Hell*)
26. "I loved you like a man loves a woman he never touches, only writes to, keeps little photographs of." (*Love is a Dog from Hell*)
27. "Love is a form of prejudice. You love what you need, you love what makes you feel good, you love what is convenient." (*Women*)
28. "I was glad I wasn’t in love, that I wasn’t happy with the world. I couldn’t have done all that I had done if I had been in love, if I had been happy." (*Women*)
29. "People with no morals often considered themselves more free, but mostly they lacked the ability to feel or love." (*Ham on Rye*)
30. "We are here to unlearn the teachings of the church, state, and our educational system. We are here to drink beer. We are here to kill war. We are here to laugh at the odds and live our lives so well that Death will tremble to take us." (*The Night Torn Mad With Footsteps*)

### **On Society and Humanity**
31. "The more crap you believe, the better off you are." (*Ham on Rye*)
32. "The whole world is full of people who think they’re good and are totally dead." (*Post Office*)
33. "Humanity, you never had it from the beginning." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)
34. "If you get married, they think you’re finished. And if you are without a woman, they think you’re incomplete." (*Women*)
35. "Society exists only as a mental concept; in the real world there are only individuals." (*Factotum*)
36. "In my work, as a writer, I only photograph, in words, what I see." (*Women*)
37. "The difference between a democracy and a dictatorship is that in a democracy you vote first and take orders later; in a dictatorship you don’t have to waste your time voting." (*Factotum*)
38. "This is very important—knowing the difference between who you are and what you are." (*Factotum*)
39. "The trouble with the world is that it doesn’t make sense, but it’s as if it makes sense." (*The Captain is Out to Lunch and the Sailors Have Taken Over the Ship*)
40. "Bad taste creates many more millionaires than good taste." (*Post Office*)

### **On Alcohol and Addiction**
41. "Drink from the well of yourself and begin again." (*The Last Night of the Earth Poems*)
42. "I’m going to die, if I have to die, but I’m going to die drinking." (*Factotum*)
43. "I needed a drink, I needed a lot of life insurance, I needed a vacation, I needed a home in the country. What I had was a coat, a hat and a gun." (*Post Office*)
44. "There’s nothing worse than too late." (*Love is a Dog from Hell*)
45. "Drinking is an emotional thing. It joggles you out of the standardism of everyday life, out of everything being the same." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)
46. "When you drank the world was still out there, but for the moment it didn’t have you by the throat." (*Factotum*)
47. "Drinking—when we’re bored, when we’re sad, when we’re happy—we drink until we’re numb." (*The People Look Like Flowers at Last*)
48. "Alcohol is probably one of the greatest things to arrive upon the earth—besides myself." (*Tales of Ordinary Madness*)
49. "Alcohol makes you an invincible person; you laugh louder, you dance faster, you move the world around." (*Women*)
50. "Drinking is like pouring gasoline on your brain; the end result is fire, pain, and more fire." (*Women*)

### **On Death and Mortality**
51. "We’re all going to die, all of us, what a circus! That alone should make us love each other but it doesn’t." (*The Captain is Out to Lunch and the Sailors Have Taken Over the Ship*)
52. "Death comes faster than you think, the scream passes just like that." (*The Last Night of the Earth Poems*)
53. "There’s no chance at all: we are all trapped by a singular fate." (*The Last Night of the Earth Poems*)
54. "You can’t beat death, but you can beat death in life." (*The People Look Like Flowers at Last*)
55. "When you get older, you realize you can’t forget anything. That’s good for writing, but it’s bad for living." (*The Captain is Out to Lunch and the Sailors Have Taken Over the Ship*)
56. "Death is inevitable, but life—life can be so interesting." (*The Captain is Out to Lunch and the Sailors Have Taken Over the Ship*)
57. "Death means nothing, and life means nothing; there’s nothing you can do, either way, except live until you die." (*The Last Night of the Earth Poems*)
58. "Live. Drink. Survive. It's as simple as that." (*Post Office*)
59. "Death is nothing, but to live defeated and inglorious is to die daily." (*The People Look Like Flowers at Last*)
60. "Death has always been the ultimate trip, the final release, the great escape." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)

### **On Loneliness and Isolation**
61. "There is a place in the heart that

 will never be filled, a space, and even during the best moments and the greatest times, we will know it." (*Love is a Dog from Hell*)
62. "The loneliness is the worst part of anything you’re going through, but the irony is that you need the loneliness to get through it." (*Women*)
63. "Isolation is the gift, all the others are a test of your endurance, of how much you really want to do it." (*The Captain is Out to Lunch and the Sailors Have Taken Over the Ship*)
64. "The way to create art is to burn and destroy ordinary concepts and to substitute them with your own." (*Factotum*)
65. "I felt like crying but I had to laugh." (*Ham on Rye*)
66. "Sometimes you just have to pee in the sink." (*Factotum*)
67. "We are all alone, born alone, die alone, and—in spite of True Romance magazines—we shall all someday look back on our lives and see that, in spite of our company, we were alone the whole way." (*Tales of Ordinary Madness*)
68. "A love like that was a serious illness, an illness from which you never entirely recover." (*Women*)
69. "The worst thing for a writer is not criticism, but the absence of it." (*Ham on Rye*)
70. "If you’re losing your soul and you know it, then you’ve still got a soul left to lose." (*Tales of Ordinary Madness*)

### **On Struggle and Resilience**
71. "What matters most is how well you walk through the fire." (*What Matters Most is How Well You Walk Through the Fire*)
72. "Endurance is more important than truth." (*Factotum*)
73. "To survive is to endure, to endure is to keep going." (*The People Look Like Flowers at Last*)
74. "If you’re going to try, go all the way. Otherwise, don’t even start." (*Factotum*)
75. "There’s a bluebird in my heart that wants to get out but I’m too tough for him." (*The Last Night of the Earth Poems*)
76. "We are here to laugh at the odds and live our lives so well that Death will tremble to take us." (*The Night Torn Mad With Footsteps*)
77. "You can't write if you don't experience life. The truth is always in the experience." (*Factotum*)
78. "Survival is my best friend, my toughest ally." (*The Captain is Out to Lunch and the Sailors Have Taken Over the Ship*)
79. "The secret is to wait until the last possible moment before everything falls apart." (*Factotum*)
80. "There is always a way out, even if it's down." (*Factotum*)

### **On Women and Relationships**
81. "A woman is a full-time job. You have to choose your profession." (*Women*)
82. "The woman who can create her own job is the woman who will win fame and fortune." (*Women*)
83. "Some men never find it, some only pretend, but there is a man who feels like it’s the only one, and for a moment the whole world is complete." (*Women*)
84. "I loved you like a man loves a woman he never touches, only writes to, keeps little photographs of." (*Love is a Dog from Hell*)
85. "Love is the biggest fraud of all time." (*Women*)
86. "A woman may become a man’s friend when the man is no longer able to find a woman to love him." (*Women*)
87. "She’s mad but she’s magic. There’s no lie in her fire." (*Love is a Dog from Hell*)
88. "It’s not that I don’t trust women. I trust them even less." (*Women*)
89. "For a woman, the only way to find the perfect man is to die and hope God sorts it out." (*Women*)
90. "A woman who can’t live without a man is like a fish out of water." (*Women*)

### **On Society and Humanity**
91. "Humanity, you never had it from the beginning." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)
92. "The masses can never comprehend what goes on in the mind of the rare individual." (*Factotum*)
93. "We are all born insane, some of us just remain that way." (*Factotum*)
94. "I wasn’t much for a job, but the one thing I was good at was being left alone." (*Post Office*)
95. "A man can go crazy with only two things: the madness of life, and the madness of death." (*The Captain is Out to Lunch and the Sailors Have Taken Over the Ship*)
96. "The less I needed, the better I felt." (*Post Office*)
97. "People are strange: they are constantly angered by trivial things, but on a major matter like totally wasting their lives, they hardly seem to notice." (*Factotum*)
98. "A civilized society is one which tolerates eccentricity to the point of doubtful sanity." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)
99. "The people who believe in politics are like the people who believe in God: they are sucking wind through bent straws." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)
100. "The worst crime is faking it." (*Notes of a Dirty Old Man*)

---

These quotes encapsulate Bukowski's brutally honest perspective on life, love, society, and the human condition. His writing continues to resonate with readers for its unfiltered look at the realities of existence.
